nodes.title: Notes
widgets_values:
This WAN2.2 workflow can do i2v with two- or three-KSamplers and has optional GGUF checkpoint loading. You can also include a last frame image to do First-Last Frame generation.


PURPLE GROUPS: These will generally need setting with the settings of your choice
ORANGE GROUPS: These are mandatory and need to stay on
BLUE GROUPS: These are optional and can be enabled/disabled using the fast bypasser (see note below about running 2 samplers vs 3 sampelrs)
RED GROUP: This is the output video


To use GGUF checkpoints, ensure that the red "Use GGUF Models?" is set to "true" and ensure you have loaded the GGUF model in the "Models Loader" group. To use regular .safetensors checkpoints, set this to "false".

Secondly, you can either run with 2 KSamplers (x + x steps) or 3 KSamplers (x + x + x steps). If you want to run in 2-sampler mode, ensure the red "Use 2 Samplers?" node is set to "true" AND you have disabled the "Step 2" group in the Fast Group Bypasser node.

NB. Make sure that your "Total Steps" node has a number that is exactly divisible by 2 or 3, depending on the number of KSamplers you want to use.

Lastly, if you want to run your generation using a Last Frame input image, ensure the red "Use Last Frame?" node is set to "true".

Download the models in the note below and ensure they are in the correct folders.

Choose a latent Video resolution, some examples I use are:

480 x 480
480 x 688
480 x 640
480 x 720

Optimal length (Latent Video Node) is 81 for WAN, but up to 121 can work.

In the "Output Video" group, choose a filename prefix as you wish (useful tip: use "%date:yyyy-MM-dd%/FILENAME_PREFIX" to save in a folder with today's date).

Insert your starting image and fill out the prompts as you wish.

For Loras - If using lightning loras, Step 1 has no lightning lora, Step 2 and Step 3 use the high noise and low noise lightning loras respectively. Add any other loras you want, but it's a good idea to add them to all two/three steps.

For the upscaling you can choose a model and then downscaler. I use remacri 4x then downscale again. With the default settings, a 480p generation will upscale to 720p using this method. Upscaling can take a long time on longer videos, so I prefer to test without it and then enable it if I like the generated video.

For the interpolation, it is a rule of thumb to use a multiplier of 3 with a length of 81 to get a decent speed on a 60 FPS final video. The final video frame rate and multiplier work together to give you the final speed/length of video so you might need to experiment based on your prompts and loras! 

The workflow will automatically rescale your input image to match the dimensions of the generation latent video. This can help with artifacting if you are using a much larger image as an input.
